batface (jessefres ... @yahoo.com) wrote:
">

: If Atilla had suceeded against Rome, would he have changed the
: landscape of the Roman Republic?

You probably meant the Roman Empire. By Atilla's time only a lawyer could
see the republican constitutional structure underneath the imperial
political structure.

In OTL, Atilla has alienated most of the other "barbarians". His inability
to establish a stable political structure in the areas he conquered
suggests he would have likewise failed in "taking over" Rome.

What is needed is a POD, probably related to Atilla's time as a noble
hostage in Rome, leading to him establishing a coalition of non-Romans
(what the Romans called "Barbarians") who would "take over" the
Empire. This isn't ASB territory as most of the "Barbarians" really wanted
to become Romanized and have the rights and privileges of Romans, and
during this period there were many steps towards assimilating them into
what had always been a multiethnic and culturally diverse empire. In this
timeline, St. Atilla not only led his Huns to Christianity, but formed a
great coalition that revives the empire and leads to a substantial
expansion into eastern Europe and central Asia.
